tweet_text: We need to rein in spending, improve the efficiency of how we deliver key social programs, and get serious about our nation‚Äôs debt immediately.

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: Biden‚Äôs recently submitted budget for next year assumes interest on the debt will stay low because the White House assumes inflation will stay very very low. What the Federal Reserve is telling us today is that may NOT be the case.

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: The Fed waited too long to move on interest rates and Washington continues to spend too much money.  Now America is about to be hit with a double whammy. Higher interest rates and expensive debt payments.

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: With today‚Äôs #ratehike the Fed is finally taking action to address out-of-control inflation. The Fed and other wonks have been saying inflation was ‚Äútransitory.‚Äù I‚Äôve discussed the need to address the Feds massive balance sheet since Dec. of 2020. https://t.co/NntTAAPVfE

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: Many economists don‚Äôt think it will get this bad, but if it rises to even 5%, the cost will be $1 Trillion in annual payments.  For comparison, the Federal Government spends ~$1.2 Trillion per year on Social Security and ~$1.4 Trillion on Medicare.

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: If we were paying interest on the debt of 10% last year, the cost of our interest on the debt would be ~$2 Trillion. Almost the cost Social Security and Medicare combined.

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: Why is there a risk debt payments will balloon?  In the 1980‚Äôs when inflation was last at ~8%, average interest on the debt was ~10%.

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: Our current Treasury debt has different maturity dates and the impact will not be felt immediately. But it will be felt soon. It will increase over time as new debt is issued. https://t.co/7i8r4IqXyX

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: Following today‚Äôs #FederalReserve action, the interest on the debt went up 0.5%. This doesn‚Äôt sound like a lot but it means we will now have an additional interest payment of about ~$100B or the cost of all federal housing programs.

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: For the last decade #interestrates have been very low. Last year interest on the debt cost taxpayers $580B with an average interest rate of ~1.5%. That‚Äôs equal to the cost of all veterans and transportation programs combined.

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: Currently, if 529 account withdrawals are not used for qualified education expenses or tuition for elementary or secondary schools, they are subject to state and federal income taxes and an additional 10% federal tax penalty on earnings of the account. 6/9

name: Bryan Steil
tweet_text: What are 529 plans? A 529 plan is a tax-advantaged savings plan designed to encourage saving for future education costs. It is like a retirement account for qualified education expenses. Typically, these plans have been used for higher education costs, like college tuition. 4/9
